defaultAppendix 1:  Specific comments on draft Deregulation Bill in order to promote rail devolution to the North of England.defaultThe provisions in the Deregulation Bill that relate to rail devolution are contained within section 
default22 and Schedule 7.  In order to deliver the rail devolution agenda for the North, Local Transport Authorities would need to have the following powers:
default&#xa0;
default1.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultto form an accountable corporate body capable of contracting with other authorities, Government and Rail Operators;
default2.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultto provide or procure rail passenger services under the Transport Acts across the geography of the area; and,
default3.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultto
default have the benefit of an exemption order from the Railways Act 1993 franchising provisions whilst retaining various powers and protections enjoyed by the Secretary of State under those provisions.
default&#xa0;
defaultAll authorities currently have the first power.  However, in the metropolitan areas of Greater Manchester, Merseyside, South Yorkshire, Tyne and Wear and West Yorkshire, the second power is potentially restricted by the 25 mile limit on the exercise of their PTE’s 
defaultpower to carry or procure the carriage of passengers by rail.  This restriction is anomalous, since LTAs outside metropolitan areas which have no PTE do not have this restriction and can use their general power of competence.
default&#xa0;
defaultAs regards the third power for rail devolution to work practically, it is important that LTAs and PTEs which manage services exempted from the national franchising regime should enjoy the benefits of some of the powers and protections in relation to any operating agreement enjoyed by the Secretary of State in relation to franchised services.  The existing legislation does not allow this.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe provisions of the Deregulation Bill will address these legislative obstacles by giving authorities most of the requisite remaining powers, and is therefore welcomed.  There are some observations to be made however:
default&#xa0;defaultAppendix 2:  Comments of suggested questions default&#xa0;
defaultGeneral default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultIt is our opinion that the changes in powers that we seek cannot be achieved through secondary legislation.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe changes in powers that we seek will provide the most robust underpinning for the operation of the proposed devolved decision-making structures.  
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultN/a
default.  
