default4. Does the draft Bill achieve its purpose of reducing the regulatory burden on business, organisations and individuals effectively and fairly? 
default&#xa0;
defaultYes.  Our proposals will lead to better prioritisation of national and local resources into rail service provision.  The legislation removes unnecessary restrictions in the Transport Act 1968 and 
defaultthe  Railways
default Act 1993.  
default&#xa0;
default5. Will the draft Bill generally benefit businesses by offsetting other regulatory burdens?  Are there indirect impacts on other businesses from reducing regulation in specific sectors? 
default&#xa0;
defaultNo significant issues arising.  
default&#xa0;default6. To what extent does the draft Bill benefit consumers as well as businesses? 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe use of the powers the bill contains will enable rail services to be managed closer to the beneficiary, whether that 
defaultbe
default local businesses or rail passengers.  We fully expect this will lead to better services that more closely match their needs.  
default&#xa0;
